10.  A bacterial cell is known to secrete a signal protein into the culture medium.  The signal protein is a 42 kDa protein consisting of 388 amino acid residues.  You have purified the protein and have determined that it contains a single disulfide bond.  In addition, you have obtained the following data on the signal protein:

a) Determine the molecular weight of the signal protein in the absence of disulfide bonds.

388 AA x 110 Da/AA = 42.680 Da = 42.680 kDa (rounded to 42.7 kDa)

b) Calculate the average hydrophobicity of the signal protein, using the values in the table below.  Assume that the AA in the table make up 100% of the protein.

\[\mathbf{0.5(34\times 1)+0.1(25\times -1)+0.1(33\times -1)+0.1(36\times 0)+0.1(50\times 0)=14.3}\]

c) Based on the information given in parts (a) and (b), propose a hypothesis to explain the secretion of this protein by the bacteria.

Based on the fact that the protein is secreted, and its calculated hydrophobicity is positive, this is likely to be a lipoprotein, with a hydrophobic domain that can associate with the membrane and thus be secreted across the cell envelope.

d) Suggest a possible role for the disulfide bond in this protein.

The disulfide bond is likely to be involved in stabilizing the conformation of the protein in the bacterial cytoplasm before export.  Once in the periplasm, the disulfide bond could be reduced, allowing the protein to become soluble (if necessary) or to undergo further folding, dimerization, etc.  The disulfide bond may also serve to keep the protein in the periplasm by making it insoluble.  Alternatively, the disulfide bond could be important for keeping the folded protein stable once it has passed through the bacterial membrane (to prevent it from unfolding or being degraded).
